ing a $15.5 million opening, followed by Sony=E2=80=99s R-rated comedy One =
of Them Days earning $13 million over the M.L.K. holiday frame=E2=80=94you =
could be forgiven for thinking it=E2=80=99s 2010 all over again. But the su=
ccess of those relatively modest releases can=E2=80=99t compensate for a ho=
liday weekend that was among the worst since the late =E2=80=9990s. This di=
ssonance once again reveals an industry in existential
crisis: Overall grosses now must be weighed against how each film performs =
in relation to the new expectations and financial requirements of this mult=
ichannel age.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

The Survive =E2=80=99til =E2=80=9925 mantra has landed movies at a crucial =
crossroads. With the pandemic and strike delays finally gone, this year=E2=
=80=99s slate will approximate the number of wide theatrical releases that =
the exhibition industry became accustomed to in
the late 2010s. But will that volume lead to 2010s-level box office? Here=
=E2=80=99s a closer look at five of the biggest themes, anxieties, and fant=
asies as the year kicks off=E2=80=A6

I. Can the
International Box Office Recover?
---------------------------------

While the theatrical industry was preoccupied with whether last
year=E2=80=99s overall domestic box office could reach 2023=E2=80=99s #Barb=
enheimer-enhanced $8.9 billion, it should have been more concerned with the=
 overseas marketplace. In 2024, non-domestic revenue fell 10 percent year o=
ver year, compared to 3.3 percent in North America.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

That decline was driven by a 25 percent drop in China, where economic strug=
gles have impacted local moviegoing and recent U.S. tentpoles
underwhelmed, with none topping $500 million. A stronger dollar is partly t=
o blame, but so is a global populace that has grown less reliant on theater=
s for their access to American pop culture. The Ryan Gosling=E2=80=93Emily =
Blunt action-comedy The Fall Guy did $92 million domestic, $181 million wor=
ldwide, and ended up with a 51/49 domestic/international split. Meanwhile, =
the Ryan Reynolds-starring, John Krasinski-directed If netted a
58/42 split, earning $111 million in North America=E2=80=94a terrific resul=
t for an original, non-action, kid-targeted flick=E2=80=94but only $192 mil=
lion worldwide. Likewise, the Daisy Edgar-Jones=E2=80=93 and Glen Powell-le=
d Twisters earned a rousing $270 million in North America, but barely crack=
ed $100 million internationally.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

By now, Hollywood has largely
written off the Chinese market for most tentpoles, treating a periodic brea=
kout like Alien: Romulus ($351 million worldwide, with $110 million from Ch=
ina) as a pleasant surprise. But the overall non-domestic dip was 10 percen=
t even outside of China, including 17.5 percent in Japan and 10.7 percent i=
n South Korea.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Yes, breakouts like Wonder Woman or Wicked: Part
One, where the domestic overperformance is such that only adequate overseas=
 grosses are required, still happen. And globally skewed hits like Mufasa: =
The Lion King=E2=80=94which has earned $382 million out of its current $591=
 million worldwide cume outside of North America=E2=80=94are still possible=
=2E But the notion of a nostalgia franc=
hise like Beetlejuice Beetlejuice play=
ing hard only in North America may presage a durable trend. The once-conven=
tional 40/60 split, even for
domestic successes, can no longer be taken for granted.

=C2=A0

Will this mean that two of this year=E2=80=99s likely global megahits, Jura=
ssic World: Rebirth and Avatar: Fire and Ash, will have to pull more of the=
ir weight stateside than previous installments? Perhaps, although those fra=
nchises tend to buck the trends by virtue of their uniqueness and generatio=
nal popularity. Moreover, it=E2=80=99s not like either title will
suffer if it earns only 75 percent of its predecessor=E2=80=94or around $75=
0 million and $1.74 billion, respectively. But they are the exceptions, not=
 the rule.

II. Has Marvel Lost Its
Luster?
-----------------------

Disney gave the MCU a sabbatical in 2024, slating just one surefire
smash=E2=80=94Deadpool & Wolverine=E2=80=94for the entire year. Part of tha=
t film=E2=80=99s success can be attributed to the fact that it featured est=
ablished franchise characters, beloved even among those unafflicted by a sl=
avish devotion to the MCU. Marvel won=E2=80=99t have that same assurance th=
is year. After all, Captain America: Brave New World, Thunderbolts, and The=
 Fantastic Four: First Steps feature new, or at least less established, cha=
racters. Still, Disney is hoping that
this trio can pull grosses closer to Phase Two (Thor: The Dark World, earni=
ng $644 million) than Phase One (Thor, earning $449 million).

=C2=A0

But will general audiences care about another Captain America movie=E2=80=
=94this one headlined by Anthony Mackie=E2=80=94nearly six years after Chri=
s Evans handed off the shield in Avengers: Endgame? Will
Thunderbolts prove to be a must-see MCU summer kickoff despite an ensemble =
cast populated with B-level characters plucked from B-level MCU movies and =
Disney+ shows? Meanwhile, The Fantastic Four: The First Steps will be the f=
ourth attempt in just over 30 years to turn Marvel=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CFirst=
 Family=E2=80=9D into a viable franchise.

=C2=A0

While Captain America: Civil War earned $1.15
billion in May of 2016, that picture was sold as a glorified =E2=80=9CAveng=
ers 2.5.=E2=80=9D The sequel pitted Earth=E2=80=99s mightiest heroes agains=
t each other while introducing MCU versions of Spider-Man and Black Panther=
=2E This time out, Brave New World will=
 be essentially just a Captain America=
 movie with a non-Steve Rogers Captain America, albeit with Harrison Ford i=
ncluded.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

As we=E2=80=99ve seen recently, the MCU isn=E2=80=99t the=C2=A0 primary sel=
ling point that it once was. Eternals barely cracked $400 million in 2021, =
and The Marvels got to only $200 million in 2023. That in-universe continui=
ty no longer had enough automatic must-see value to pull grosses in the $67=
5 million to $875 million range=E2=80=94i.e., on par with what used to be e=
xpected for non-Avengers Marvel movies.

=C2=A0

If only established MCU franchises, such as Doctor Strange or Thor, reach u=
pper-level Phase Two grosses, Disney will be in a bind. You can only recapt=
ure 2010s glory by casting Robert Downey Jr. as Doctor Doom so many times. =
And the multiplex industry that once depended on the MCU franchise as an ov=
er-indexing buffer will have to hope that other tentpoles can make up the d=
ifference, while non-tentpoles overperform here and there.=C2=A0

III. Are Old Franchises
the New Comedies?
-----------------------

These days, it often takes familiar, nostalgic packaging to fill
theaters. Audiences will show up for a good laugh only if the film is a hyb=
rid action-comedy, horror-comedy, or within an established and often fantas=
tical franchise. (Think Barbie, Inside Out, Despicable Me, Deadpool, Beetle=
juice, M3GAN, and Bad Boys.) This year, Hollywood will apply that logic to =
smaller-scale, less tentpole-sized properties. At least, that=E2=80=99s the=
 optimistic view of how this year=E2=80=99s revivals will pan out.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Disney=E2=80=99s Freaky Friday: Freakier Friday is a pure nostalgia play th=
at targets the grown-ups who made the Lindsay Lohan=E2=80=93Jamie Lee Curti=
s remake a hit more than 20 years ago. The same could be said of Paramount=
=E2=80=99s Naked Gun reboot, starring Liam Neeson and Pamela Anderson. Sony=
=E2=80=99s comedic Anaconda revamp, starring Jack
Black and Paul Rudd, could be another example of a studio scraping the bott=
om of the barrel for any past hit that could be retrofitted into a franchis=
e reboot. Sony, however, could potentially learn from its blockbuster Juman=
ji revival, and craft something good enough to appeal to moviegoers who cou=
ldn=E2=80=99t care less about the original. Along with Paramount=E2=80=99s =
planned Scary Movie revival, these remakes could remind audiences that they=
 used to show
up to theaters for the exclusive purpose of laughing for 90-120 minutes. (T=
his year also features legacy sequels of Karate Kid and I Know What You Did=
 Last Summer, but neither is a reboot or remake.)

IV. Will
F1 Change Apple=E2=80=99s Thin-Skinned Stance on Theaters?
----------------------------------------------------

Set for a late June theatrical release, courtesy of Warner Bros.,
the very pricey Joseph Kosinski-directed Formula One melodrama starring Bra=
d Pitt may be the final test for Apple=E2=80=99s theatrical release strateg=
y. After a string of embarrassing flops like Argylle and Fly Me to the Moon=
, bad press on F1 could take Apple out of the theatrical game for good.=C2=
=A0

So the stakes are high. As we saw with Margot Robbie=E2=80=99s Wuthering He=
ights, which Warner
Bros. snatched from Netflix with less money but the promise of theaters, th=
e out-of-home debut remains a powerful carrot. Netflix likely won=E2=80=99t=
 budge beyond limited=E2=80=94or, perhaps, token=E2=80=94theatrical release=
s. Success for the just-announced, Imax-only, four-week theatrical window f=
or Greta Gerwig=E2=80=99s Narnia over Thanksgiving 2026 is unlikely to turn=
 Ted Sarandos into a multiplex true believer. And my guess is that Apple, d=
