The Feedback
------------

Good responses to my Thursday report on Greta
Gerwig=E2=80=99s deal with Imax and Netflix for =E2=80=98Narnia=E2=80=99 an=
d my ideas for Hollywood=E2=80=99s role in the L.A. fire rebuild. Some exam=
ples=E2=80=A6

=C2=A0

=E2=80=9CGood for Greta, but the real shame is that a four-week [theatrical=
] window is now considered a =E2=80=98win.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94A fil=
mmaker

=C2=A0

=E2=80=9CShe thinks she=E2=80=99s getting
an actual theatrical release=E2=80=A6 not remotely quite. This is just a pl=
atform release on steroids. Wait till she finds out they won=E2=80=99t be r=
eporting box office.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94An executive

=C2=A0

=E2=80=9CAbsolutely agree on committing to more production in L.A., but the=
 incentive structure should be focused on volume and not just a few big pro=
ductions. California should structure it similar to the U.K. incentive wher=
e they
support big productions, but also streamline indie film applications and mo=
ney up to a certain budget threshold (like $20 million). Additionally, L.A.=
 should create some type of regional credit for small films (tier 1) so tho=
se little films stop jetting off to Louisville or Oklahoma. Those are the b=
edrock productions of a talent pipeline in our town and industry.=E2=80=9D =
=E2=80=94An executive

=C2=A0

=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99d be curious to
hear more about how Brady Corbet delivers a period epic for $10 million, an=
d yet L.A.-shot Joker 2 cost 20 times that. The industry is going to have t=
o figure out how to deliver quality content at scale and at cost=E2=80=94ma=
ybe L.A. can help lead the way in that regard, given its concentration of a=
mbitious, emerging talent and empty soundstages. Wouldn=E2=80=99t that be t=
he right direction for L.A.=E2=80=94offer serious, low-cost alternatives to=
 development and production that would set the stage for the
future of the storytelling industry?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94A producer

=C2=A0

=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m proposing a streamlined rehousing fund to provide imme=
diate relief to displaced crew and non-union workers. While the industry un=
ions and organizations like The Motion Picture & Television Fund are steppi=
ng in, this initiative would fast-track rehousing efforts, addressing an ur=
gent need for those who keep our industry running. Long term, this fund, wi=
th
investment from larger industry players, could be used to build affordable =
housing for future industry professionals, ensuring Los Angeles remains a g=
lobal hub for skilled crews and innovative storytelling. This isn=E2=80=99t=
 just about providing shelter, it=E2=80=99s about securing the future of Ho=
llywood by supporting the people who=E2=80=99ve always made it possible.=E2=
=80=9D =E2=80=94A screenwriter

=E2=80=8A

