line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">While the theatrical industry was preoccupied w=
ith whether last
year=E2=80=99s overall domestic box office could reach 2023=E2=80=99s #Barb=
enheimer-enhanced $8.9 billion, it should have been more concerned with the=
 overseas marketplace. In 2024, non-domestic revenue fell 10 percent year o=
ver year, compared to 3.3 percent in North America.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px=
;">That decline was driven by a 25 percent drop in China, where economic st=
ruggles have impacted local moviegoing and recent U.S. tentpoles
underwhelmed, with none topping $500 million. A stronger dollar is partly t=
o blame, but so is a global populace that has grown less reliant on theater=
s for their access to American pop culture. The <strong>Ryan Gosling</stron=
g>=E2=80=93<strong>Emily Blunt</strong> action-comedy <em>The Fall Guy</em>=
 did $92 million domestic, $181 million worldwide, and ended up with a 51/4=
9 domestic/international split. Meanwhile, the <strong>Ryan Reynolds</stron=
g>-starring, <strong>John Krasinski</strong>-directed <em>If</em> netted a
58/42 split, earning $111 million in North America=E2=80=94a terrific resul=
t for an original, non-action, kid-targeted flick=E2=80=94but only $192 mil=
lion worldwide. Likewise, the <strong>Daisy Edgar-Jones</strong>=E2=80=93 a=
nd <strong>Glen Powell</strong>-led <em>Twisters</em> earned a rousing $270=
 million in North America, but barely cracked $100 million internationally.=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">By now, Hollywood has largely
written off the Chinese market for most tentpoles, treating a periodic brea=
kout like <em>Alien: Romulus</em> ($351 million worldwide, with $110 millio=
n from China) as a pleasant surprise. But the overall non-domestic dip was =
10 percent even outside of China, including 17.5 percent in Japan and 10.7 =
percent in South Korea.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Yes, breakouts like <em>=
Wonder Woman</em> or <em>Wicked:</em> <em>Part
One</em>, where the domestic overperformance is such that only adequate ove=
rseas grosses are required, still happen. And globally skewed hits like <em=
>Mufasa: The Lion King=E2=80=94</em>which has earned $382 million out of it=
s current $591 million worldwide cume outside of North America=E2=80=94are =
still possible. But the notion of a nostalgia franchise like <em>Beetlejuic=
e Beetlejuice</em> playing hard <em>only </em>in North America may presage =
a durable trend. The once-conventional 40/60 split, even for
domestic successes, can no longer be taken for granted.</p><p style=3D"marg=
in:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Will this mean th=
at two of this year=E2=80=99s likely global megahits, <em>Jurassic World: R=
ebirth </em>and <em>Avatar: Fire and Ash</em>, will have to pull more of th=
eir weight stateside than previous installments? Perhaps, although those fr=
anchises tend to buck the trends by virtue of their uniqueness and generati=
onal popularity. Moreover, it=E2=80=99s not like either title will
suffer if it earns only 75 percent of its predecessor=E2=80=94or around $75=
0 million and $1.74 billion, respectively. But they are the exceptions, not=
 the rule.</p></div>
